{"title_page": "Rhapsomates", "text_new": "'''Rhapsomates''' (or '''Rapsomates''') led a revolt against the [[Byzantine Empire]] on [[Theme of Cyprus|Cyprus]] in the early 1090s. He was defeated by the ''[[megas doux]]'' [[John Doukas (megas doux)|Joannes Doukas]] and taken captive.{{sfn|Gregory|1991}}\n\nRhapsomates' revolt was contemporary with that of [[Karykes]] on [[Byzantine Crete|Crete]]. It broke out in late 1090 or early 1091. In February or March 1091, [[John the Oxite]] delivered a scathing rebuke to the Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]], during which he noted the outbreak of revolts in Crete and Cyprus.{{sfn|Tsougarakis|1988|p=80}} Both took place while the central government was occupied in wars with the [[Pechenegs]] in Europe and the [[Seljuk Turks|Turks]] of Emir [[Tzachas]] in Asia.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=383}} Although the mere arrival of the fleet of Joannes Doukas off Crete caused the revolt of Karykes to melt away, the ''doux'' faced much greater resistance on Cyprus. Forced to land his troops, Rhapsomates led the resistance of the islanders against him, according to the contemporary historian [[Anna Komnene]], who does not record how long this resistance lasted.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=386}}\n\nIn the aftermath of the revolt, Alexios I appointed [[Eumathios Philokales]] as ''[[stratopedarches]]'' (governor) and sent a large garrison.{{sfn|Gregory|1991}}{{sfn|Georgiou|2008|p=167}} He also endowed him with special taxing powers, a hint perhaps that the revolt had been directed at Alexios' fiscal policies.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=385}} He also appointed a certain Kalliparios to fiscal (''[[exisotes]]'') and judicial (''[[:wikt:\u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2|krites]]'') office.{{sfn|Georgiou|2008|p=167}} A flurry of construction on the island in the 1090s may be linked to the crushing of Rhapsomates' revolt.{{sfn|Wharton|1991}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Peter |last=Frankopan |authorlink=Peter Frankopan |title=Challenges to Imperial Authority in Byzantium: Revolts on Crete and Cyprus at the End of the 11th C. |journal=Byzantion |volume=74 |issue=2 |year=2004 |pages=382\u2013402 |jstor=44172968}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Stavros G. |last=Georgiou |title=Eumathios Philokales as Stratopedarches of Cyprus (ca. 1092) |journal=Byzantinoslavica |volume=66|year=2008 |pages=167\u2013172 |url=http://www.academia.edu/download/61851677/Eumathios_Philokales20200121-82076-1riu1zb.pdf}}\n*{{ODB |first=Timothy E. |last=Gregory |title=Cyprus}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Alexis G. C. |last=Savvides |title=Can we refer to a concerted action among Rapsomates, Caryces and the Emir Tzachas between AD 1091 and 1093? |journal=Byzantion |volume=70 |issue=1 |year=2000 |pages=122\u2013134 |jstor=44172366}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Dimitris |last=Tsougarakis |title=Byzantine Crete: From the 5th Century to the Venetian Conquest |publisher=Historical Publications St. D. Basilopoulos |location=Athens |year=1988}}\n*{{ODB |first=Annabel Jane |last=Wharton |title=Monuments of Cyprus}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Byzantine Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Byzantine rebels]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rhapsomates''' (or '''Rapsomates''') led a revolt against the [[Byzantine Empire]] on [[Theme of Cyprus|Cyprus]] in the early 1090s. He was defeated by the ''[[megas doux]]'' [[John Doukas (megas doux)|Joannes Doukas]] and taken captive.{{sfn|Gregory|1991}}\n\nRhapsomates revolt was contemporary with that of [[Karykes]] on [[Byzantine Crete|Crete]]. It broke out in late 1090 or early 1091. In February or March 1091, [[John the Oxite]] delivered a scathing rebuke to the Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]], during which he noted the outbreak of revolts in Crete and Cyprus.{{sfn|Tsougarakis|1988|p=80}} Both took place while the central government was occupied in wars with the [[Pechenegs]] in Europe and the [[Seljuk Turks|Turks]] of Emir [[Tzachas]] in Asia.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=383}} Although the mere arrival of the fleet of Joannes Doukas off Crete caused the revolt of Karykes to melt away, the ''doux'' faced much greater resistance on Cyprus. Forced to land his troops, Rhapsomates led the resistance of the islanders against him, according to the contemporary historian [[Anna Komnene]], who does not record how long this resistance lasted.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=386}}\n\nIn the aftermath of the revolt, Alexios I appointed [[Eumathios Philokales]] as ''[[stratopedarches]]'' (governor) and sent a large garrison.{{sfn|Gregory|1991}}{{sfn|Georgiou|2008|p=167}} He also endowed him with special taxing powers, a hint perhaps that the revolt had been directed at Alexios' fiscal policies.{{sfn|Frankopan|2004|p=385}} He also appointed a certain Kalliparios to fiscal (''[[exisotes]]'') and judicial (''[[:wikt:\u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2|krites]]'') office.{{sfn|Georgiou|2008|p=167}} A flurry of construction on the island in the 1090s may be linked to the crushing of Rhapsomates' revolt.{{sfn|Wharton|1991}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Peter |last=Frankopan |authorlink=Peter Frankopan |title=Challenges to Imperial Authority in Byzantium: Revolts on Crete and Cyprus at the End of the 11th C. |journal=Byzantion |volume=74 |issue=2 |year=2004 |pages=382\u2013402 |jstor=44172968}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Stavros G. |last=Georgiou |title=Eumathios Philokales as Stratopedarches of Cyprus (ca. 1092) |journal=Byzantinoslavica |volume=66|year=2008 |pages=167\u2013172 |url=http://www.academia.edu/download/61851677/Eumathios_Philokales20200121-82076-1riu1zb.pdf}}\n*{{ODB |first=Timothy E. |last=Gregory |title=Cyprus}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Alexis G. C. |last=Savvides |title=Can we refer to a concerted action among Rapsomates, Caryces and the Emir Tzachas between AD 1091 and 1093? |journal=Byzantion |volume=70 |issue=1 |year=2000 |pages=122\u2013134 |jstor=44172366}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |firs