of the same name]]. He is also known for appearing in the films ''[[Bindlestiffs]]'' (2012), and ''[[Premature (film)|Premature]]'' (2014).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Bindlestiffs]]''\n| John Woo\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Premature (film)|Premature]]''\n| Rob Crabbe\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Sugar Mountain (film)|Sugar Mountain]]''\n| Josh Miller\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]''\n| Greg Anrue\n| \n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| data-sort-value=\"Neighbors, The\" | ''[[The Neighbors (2012 TV series)|The Neighbors]]''\n| Hank\n| Episode: \"You've Lost That Larry Feeling\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| [[Holden March]]\n| Episode: \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 16)#ep347|Holden's Manifesto]]\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Modern Family]]''\n| Alec\n| Episode: \"[[Strangers in the Night (Modern Family)|Strangers in the Night]]\"\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''[[Scream (TV series)|Scream]]''\n| Noah Foster\n| Main role (seasons 1\u20132)\n|-\n| 2016\n|  ''[[Chicago Fire (TV series)|Chicago Fire]]''\n| Alan\n| Episode: \"I Held Her Hand\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Dirty John (TV series)|Dirty John]]''\n| Jimmy\n| Episode: \"Approachable Dreams\"\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Valley of the Boom]]''\n|[[Marc Andreessen]]\n| Main role<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/valley-of-the-boom-bradley-whitford-steve-zahn-lamorne-norris-nat-geos-silicon-valley-themed-limited-series-1202339218/ |title=''Valley Of The Boom'': Bradley Whitford, Steve Zahn & Lamorne Morris To Star In Nat Geo's Silicon Valley-Themed Limited Series |first1=Nellie |last1=Andreeva |first2=Denise |last2=Petski |date=March 16, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=March 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317105238/http://deadline.com/2018/03/valley-of-the-boom-bradley-whitford-steve-zahn-lamorne-norris-nat-geos-silicon-valley-themed-limited-series-1202339218/ |archivedate=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Web===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Scream: If I Die''\n| Noah Foster\n| Episode: \"Welcome to the Morgue\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2882198/scream-last-words-if-i-die/ |title=Famous Last Words: Watch Each Scream Teen Say Goodbye{{nbsp}}... Just In Case They Die|work=[[MTV]] |last=Debler |first=Lance |date=May 25, 2016 |accessdate=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karna, John}}\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Houston]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "name_user": "Joeyconnick", "label": "safe", "comment": "copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Karna"}
{"title_page": "Glorious Fool", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Glorious Fool\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[John Martyn]]\n| cover      = Gloriousfool.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 1981\n| recorded   = The Townhouse, London\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[blues]]\n| length     = 55:16 <ref>https://www.amazon.de/Glorious-Fool-John-Martyn/dp/B00CJMGKWY/ref=mb_oe_o</ref>\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]]\n| producer   = [[Phil Collins]]\n| prev_title = [[Grace and Danger]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[Well Kept Secret]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r107665|pure_url=yes}}]\n| rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n| rev3=''[[Melody Maker]]''|rev2Score= (favourable) <ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Sutherland |url=http://www.johnmartyn.info/node/611 |title=Glorious Fool - WEA K99178 &#124; Big Muff |publisher=Johnmartyn.info |date=1981-09-19 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n| rev4=''[[NME]]''|rev3Score= (mixed)<ref>{{cite web|author=Graham Lock |url=http://www.johnmartyn.info/node/612 |title=Glorious Fool - WEA K99178 &#124; Big Muff |publisher=Johnmartyn.info |date=1981-10-10 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>|noprose=yes}}\n'''''Glorious Fool''''' is a 1981 studio album by musician [[John Martyn]].  After a long association with [[Island Records]], this was Martyn's first of two albums for [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]].  The album was produced by [[Phil Collins]] and engineered by [[Nick Launay]] and Steve Travell.  The album is named for the title track satirizing [[Ronald Reagan]]'s ascent to the White House as the 40th U.S. President.\n\nOpening track \"Couldn't Love You More\" is a re-worked arrangement of the song that originally appeared on 1977's ''[[One World (John Martyn album)|One World]]''. The original acoustic version is here re-recorded as a full-band track, featuring a guest appearance from [[Eric Clapton]]. Clapton covered Martyn's \"May You Never\" on his 1977 album ''[[Slowhand]]''. When Martyn was presented with a lifetime achievement award by Collins at the 2008 [[BBC Folk Awards]], Clapton sent a message saying that he was \"so far ahead of everything else it was inconceivable\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/4389429/John-Martyn.html |title=John Martyn |newspaper=Telegraph |date=2009-01-29 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref> \"Couldn't Love You More\", in its various forms, remained a fixture of Martyn's live performances. Irish Musician [[Lisa Hannigan]] has described the song as one of her favourites, covering the song with [[Faultline (musician)|Faultline]] in 2006.\n\nIn August 1981, \"Please Fall In Love With Me\"/\"Don't You Go\" was released as a single.\n\nMore mainstream in production compared to Martyn's previous albums, and helped by promotion in the way of a 32-date UK tour, ''Glorious Fool'' charted at #25 on its release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnmartyn.com/?location=/web/1980s |title=1980s |publisher=John Martyn |date= |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by John Martyn.\n\n#\"Couldn't Love You More\"  \u2013 3:59\n#\"Amsterdam\" \u2013 5:27\n#\"Hold On To My Heart\"  \u2013 4:39\n#\"Perfect Hustler\"\u2013 4:42\n#\"Hearts and Keys\"  \u2013 7:33\n#\"Glorious Fool\" \u2013 4:58\n#\"Never Say Never\" \u2013 4:56\n#\"Pascanel (Get Back Home)\"  \u2013 3:48\n#\"Didn't Do That\" \u2013 4:20\n#\"Please Fall in Love With Me\"  \u2013 6:07\n#\"Don't You Go\"  \u2013 4:43\n\n==Personnel==\n*John Martyn - vocals, guitar\n*[[Phil Collins]] - drums, vocoder and additional vocals, piano on \"Don't You Go\"\n*[[Alan Thomson (musician)|Alan Thomson]] - bass\n*[[Max Middleton]] - keyboards\n*[[Danny Cummings]] - percussion\n*[[Dick Cuthell]] - flugelhorn on \"Hold on My Heart\", trumpet on \"Didn't Do That\"\n*[[Eric Clapton]] - guitar on \"Couldn't Love You More\"\n;Technical\n*[[Nick Launay]] - engineer\n*Steve Travell - assistant engineer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johnmartyn.com/ The Official John Martyn Website]\n\n{{John Martyn}}\n\n[[Category:John Martyn albums]]\n[[Category:1981 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Phil Collins]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Glorious Fool\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[John Martyn]]\n| cover      = Gloriousfool.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 1981\n| recorded   = The Townhouse, London\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[blues]]\n| length     = 55:16 <ref>https://www.amazon.de/Glorious-Fool-John-Martyn/dp/B00CJMGKWY/ref=mb_oe_o</ref>\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]]\n| producer   = [[Phil Collins]]\n| prev_title = [[Grace and Danger]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[Well Kept Secret]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r107665|pure_url=yes}}]\n|rev2=''[[Melody Maker]]''|rev2Score= (favourable) <ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Sutherland |url=http://www.johnmartyn.info/node/611 |title=Glorious Fool - WEA K99178 &#124; Big Muff |publisher=Johnmartyn.info |date=1981-09-19 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n|rev3=''[[NME]]''|rev3Score= (mixed)<ref>{{cite web|author=Graham Lock |url=http://www.johnmartyn.info/node/612 |title=Glorious Fool - WEA K99178 &#124; Big Muff |publisher=Johnmartyn.info |date=1981-10-10 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>|noprose=yes}}\n'''''Glorious Fool''''' is a 1981 studio album by musician [[John Martyn]].  After a long association with [[Island Records]], this was Martyn's first of two albums for [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]].  The album was produced by [[Phil Collins]] and engineered by [[Nick Launay]] and Steve Travell.  The album is named for the title track satirizing [[Ronald Reagan]]'s ascent to the White House as the 40th U.S. President.\n\nOpening track \"Couldn't Love You More\" is a re-worked arrangement of the song that originally appeared on 1977's ''[[One World (John Martyn album)|One World]]''. The original acoustic version is here re-recorded as a full-band track, featuring a guest appearance from [[Eric Clapton]]. Clapton covered Martyn's \"May You Never\" on his 1977 album ''[[Slowhand]]''. When Martyn was presented with a lifetime achievement award by Collins at the 2008 [[BBC Folk Awards]], Clapton sent a message saying that he was \"so far ahead of everything else it was inconceivable\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/4389429/John-Martyn.html |title=John Martyn |newspaper=Telegraph |date=2009-01-29 |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref> \"Couldn't Love You More\", in its various forms, remained a fixture of Martyn's live performances. Irish Musician [[Lisa Hannigan]] has described the song as one of her favourites, covering the song with [[Faultline (musician)|Faultline]] in 2006.\n\nIn August 1981, \"Please Fall In Love With Me\"/\"Don't You Go\" was released as a single.\n\nMore mainstream in production compared to Martyn's previous albums, and helped by promotion in the way of a 32-date UK tour, ''Glorious Fool'' charted at #25 on its release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnmartyn.com/?location=/web/1980s |title=1980s |publisher=John Martyn |date= |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by John Martyn.\n\n#\"Couldn't Love You More\"  \u2013 3:59\n#\"Amsterdam\" \u2013 5:27\n#\"Hold On To My Heart\"  \u2013 4:39\n#\"Perfect Hustler\"\u2013 4:42\n#\"Hearts and Keys\"  \u2013 7:33\n#\"Glorious Fool\" \u2013 4:58\n#\"Never Say Never\" \u2013 4:56\n#\"Pascanel (Get Back Home)\"  \u2013 3:48\n#\"Didn't Do That\" \u2013 4:20\n#\"Please Fall in Love With Me\"  \u2013 6:07\n#\"Don't You Go\"  \u2013 4:43\n\n==Personnel==\n*John Martyn - vocals, guitar\n*[[Phil Collins]] - drums, vocoder and additional vocals, piano on \"Don't You Go\"\n*[[Alan Thomson (musician)|Alan Thomson]] - bass\n*[[Max Middleton]] - keyboards\n*[[Danny Cummings]] - percussion\n*[[Dick Cuthell]] - flugelhorn on \"Hold on My Heart\", trumpet on \"Didn't Do That\"\n*[[Eric Clapton]] - guitar on \"Couldn't Love You More\"\n;Technical\n*[[Nick Launay]] - engineer\n*Steve Travell - assistant engineer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johnmartyn.com/ The Official John Martyn Website]\n\n{{John Martyn}}\n\n[[Category:John Martyn albums]]\n[[Category:1981 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Phil Collins]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Muso805", "label": "safe", "comment": "4 star rating from 10 volume 4th Edition Oxford University Press, EPM 2007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glorious_Fool"}
{"title_page": "Blowing house", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[Image:Blowing House near Black Tor.jpg|right|thumb|The remains of a blowing house near Black Tor on Dartmoor.]]\nA '''blowing house''' or '''blowing mill''' was a building used for [[smelting]] [[tin]] in Cornwall and on [[Dartmoor]] in Devon, in [[South West England]]. Blowing houses contained a furnace and a pair of bellows that were powered by an adjacent water wheel, and they were in use from the early 14th century until they were gradually replaced by [[reverberatory furnace]]s in the 18th century. The remains of over 40 blowing houses have been identified on Dartmoor.\n\n==History==\nThe blowing house method of smelting tin was probably introduced early in the 14th century to replace the earliest method of smelting which had to be done in two stages \u2013 a first smelting probably took place near to the tinworks and the roughly smelted metal was taken to a [[stannary town]] to be smelted again to produce the final refined product.<ref name=\"newman\"/> Each of these smeltings was taxed separately until 1303 when they were replaced by a single tax on the finished product. It is likely that this tax change was due to the improved smelting process provided by the blowing houses.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n\n{{rquote|right|totum illud molendinium ibidem vocatum a blowyng myll & knakkyng myll|Extract from a 1514 [[Leasehold estate|lease of land]] at [[Dartmeet]]<br />(held by the [[Devon Record Office]]).<ref name=\"newman\"/>}}\nDocumentation confirms the existence of blowing houses in Cornwall as early as 1402, but the earliest reference for Dartmoor is not found until the early 16th century, though it is likely that they were in use on the moor earlier.<ref name=\"newman\"/> In Devon there are many references to blowing mills throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, reflecting the boom time in tin-mining on Dartmoor. However, by 1730 there were only two blowing mills working in the whole of the county: at Sheepstor and Plympton.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n<!-- The oldest known blowing house on Dartmoor, known as \"Kings Oven\", stood above the [[Warren House Inn]] and is known from the 1240 Perambulation of Dartmoor.<ref name=gill/> (I think there's now doubt that this was a BH. Remmed till can confirm one way or the other.) -->\n\nFrom the beginning of the 18th century, this method was gradually superseded by [[reverberatory furnace]] smelting, which used higher temperatures and powdered anthracite as fuel and had the advantage of not requiring a forced draught of air. The smelting house at [[Eylesbarrow tin mine]] which was in operation during the first half of the 19th century had two furnaces, one of each type.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| author = R.M.L. Cook, T.A.P. Grieves & C.C. Kilvington\n| title = Eylesbarrow (1814\u20131852). A Study of a Dartmoor Tin Mine\n| journal = Rep. Trans. Devon. Ass. Advmt Sci.\n| volume = 106\n| pages = 193\u2013198.\n| year = 1974\n| postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nOn Dartmoor, blowing houses were rectangular buildings between around {{convert|16|to|32|ft}} in length and around half this in width.<ref name =\"worth\"/> They were made of unmortared granite blocks with walls often {{convert|2|ft|6|in}} or more thick and probably had turf or thatch roofs which were periodically burnt to retrieve the particles of tin that would have been driven into the roof through the blast from the bellows.<ref name=gill/> Blowing houses are typically located on or near the bank of a stream where the fall of water was enough for a leat to be built to work a small ({{convert|9|ft|abbr=on|disp=or}}) diameter overshot [[water wheel]] which developed around {{Convert|0.66|hp|kW|1|abbr=on}} to operate the bellows.<ref name=gill>{{cite book\n| last =Gill\n| first =Crispin (editor)\n| title =Dartmoor, A New Study\n| publisher =David & Charles\n| year =1970\n| location =Newton Abbot\n| pages =[https://archive.org/details/dartmoornewstudy0000gill/page/102 102\u2013104]\n| isbn =0-7153-5041-2\n| url-access =registration\n| url =https://archive.org/details/dartmoornewstudy0000gill/page/102\n}}</ref>\n\nThe only contemporary detailed description of a blowing house was provided by a Cornishman named [[William Pryce]] in his treatise on Cornish mining of 1778:<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n{{cquote|The fire-place, or castle, is about six feet perpendicular, two feet wide in the top part each way, and about fourteen inches in the bottom, all made of moorstone and clay, well cemented and clamped together. The pipe or nose of each bellows is fixed ten inches (254 mm) high from the bottom of the castle, in a large piece of wrought iron, called the Hearth-eye. The tin and charcoal are laid in the castle, stratum super stratum, in such quantities as are thought proper; so that from eight to twelve hundred weight of Tin, by the consumption of eighteen to twenty-four sixty gallon packs of charcoal, may be smelted in a tide or twelve hours time.<ref>{{Cite book\n| author = [[William Pryce]]\n| title = Mineralogia Cornubiensis: A Treatise on Minerals, Mines, and Mining\n| location = London\n| year = 1778\n| url = https://archive.org/details/mineralogiacorn00prycgoog\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/mineralogiacorn00prycgoog/page/n183 136]\n| publisher = Printed and sold for the author by J. Phillips\n}} (online at Google Books)</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Crispin Gill, about two tons of [[charcoal]] was needed to smelt a ton of metal. The molten metal ran out from the bottom of the furnace into a granite trough or \"float\" from where it was ladled into stone moulds.<ref name=gill/>\n\n==Archaeology==\nArchaeological investigation of blowing houses started in 1866 when John Kelly examined the lower mill at Yealm Steps. Robert Burnard cleared the interior of the lower mill at Week Ford in the 1880s, but the most notable researcher of the remains on Dartmoor was [[Richard Hansford Worth|R. Hansford Worth]] who made detailed records of over 40 sites.<ref name=\"newman\">{{Cite book\n| last = Newman\n| first = Phil\n| title = The Dartmoor Tin Industry \u2013 A Field Guide\n| publisher = Chercombe Press\n| location = Newton Abbot\n| year = 1998\n| pages = 5, 7, 35\u201340\n| isbn = 0-9532708-0-7\n}}</ref> Since then, research on the tin industry in the south west has continued, for instance The Dartmoor Tinworking Interest Group was formed in 1991.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n\n[[File:Lower blowing house, River Walkham - furnace, float & mould.jpg|thumb|The furnace area of the Lower Merrivale blowing house (see text)]]\nThere is evidence for furnaces that match the description given by Pryce (see above) at Upper and Lower [[Merrivale, Devon|Merrivale]], Avon Dam and Blacksmith's Shop. Each of these sites has two upright granite slabs about {{convert|2|to|3|ft}} apart set into the floor area of the mill, leaving space behind for the bellows. The Merrivale sites also have a slab at the back, making a basic hearth shape.<ref name=\"newman\"/> The accompanying photograph shows the two side slabs of the furnace at the Lower Merrivale blowing house, with the somewhat displaced float stone between them. The mouldstone, filled with rainwater, is just above and to the right.\n\nThe mouldstone is the best field evidence for a blowing house; they are large blocks of granite with a flat top containing a rectangular hollow recess into which the molten tin was poured to be cast into ingots. The moulds vary in size and shape, the largest known from Dartmoor being that from Upper Merrivale at {{convert|280|x|390|mm}}, and the smallest {{convert|180|mm}} square at Longstone. Some mouldstones have additional smaller hollows on their surface; these are traditionally assumed to be for assaying purposes, but some authors have suggested that they may have been for making small ingots for selling illicitly to avoid [[tin coinage]], the tax on [[White tin|white, or refined tin]].<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n\nThe only properly documented find of a tin ingot from Dartmoor has a diagonal hole through it which matches the supposed practice of placing a stick in the mould when pouring in the molten tin. The stick would burn away leaving the hole which would be used to lever out the solid ingot from the mould and would later be useful to tie up the ingots for carriage.<ref name=\"newman\"/> According to Worth, the found ingot fitted precisely into one of the moulds found at the lower blowing house on the [[River Yealm]], although it did not fill it and weighed only {{convert|52|lb}}, far less than the average Dartmoor ingot weight of {{convert|195|lb}}. He speculated that it was the small surplus that remained after the normal ingots had been cast.<ref name =\"worth\">{{cite book\n| title=Worth's Dartmoor\n| last = Worth\n| first = R. N.\n| editor1-last = Spooner\n| editor1-first = G. M.\n| editor2-last = Russell\n| editor2-first = F. S.\n| editor2-link = F. S. Russell\n| year=1967\n| pages=316\u20137\n| publisher=David & Charles\n| isbn= 0715351486\n| location=Newton Abbot}}</ref> Cornish ingots were much larger, averaging around {{convert|345|lb|kg}}.<ref name =\"worth\"/>\n\nOne of the best preserved blowing houses on Dartmoor is above [[Merrivale, Devon|Merrivale]] Bridge on the [[River Walkham]]. It has a mould stone close to its entrance and the wheel-pit can be easily traced.<ref name=gill/> Some blowing houses also housed crushing (\"knacking\") or grinding (\"crazing\") mills, and at Gobbet Mine on the [[River Swincombe]] both the upper and lower grinding stones were found.<ref name=gill/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n*[[Dartmoor tin-mining]]\n*[[Blowing engine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bryan Earl ''Cornish mining: the techniques of metal mining in the West of England, past and present''; 2nd edition; Cornish Hillside Publications, 1994. {{ISBN|0-9519419-3-3}}.pp.&nbsp;97, 97.1 with illustration.\n\n[[Category:Tin mining]]\n[[Category:Industrial furnaces]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Dartmoor]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[Image:Blowing House near Black Tor.jpg|right|thumb|The remains of a blowing house near Black Tor on Dartmoor.]]\nA '''blowing house''' or '''blowing mill''' was a building used for [[smelting]] [[tin]] in Cornwall and on [[Dartmoor]] in Devon, in [[South West England]]. Blowing houses contained a furnace and a pair of bellows that were powered by an adjacent water wheel, and they were in use from the early 14th century until they were gradually replaced by [[reverberatory furnace]]s in the 18th century. The remains of over 40 blowing houses have been identified on Dartmoor.\n\n==History==\nThe blowing house method of smelting tin was probably introduced early in the 14th century to replace the earliest method of smelting which had to be done in two stages \u2013 a first smelting probably took place near to the tinworks and the roughly smelted metal was taken to a [[stannary town]] to be smelted again to produce the final refined product.<ref name=\"newman\"/> Each of these smeltings was taxed separately until 1303 when they were replaced by a single tax on the finished product. It is likely that this tax change was due to the improved smelting process provided by the blowing houses.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n\n{{rquote|right|totum illud molendinium ibidem vocatum a blowyng myll & knakkyng myll|Extract from a 1514 [[Leasehold estate|lease of land]] at [[Dartmeet]]<br />(held by the [[Devon Record Office]]).<ref name=\"newman\"/>}}\nDocumentation confirms the existence of blowing houses in Cornwall as early as 1402, but the earliest reference for Dartmoor is not found until the early 16th century, though it is likely that they were in use on the moor earlier.<ref name=\"newman\"/> In Devon there are many references to blowing mills throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, reflecting the boom time in tin-mining on Dartmoor. However, by 1730 there were only two blowing mills working in the whole of the county: at Sheepstor and Plympton.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n<!-- The oldest known blowing house on Dartmoor, known as \"Kings Oven\", stood above the [[Warren House Inn]] and is known from the 1240 Perambulation of Dartmoor.<ref name=gill/> (I think there's now doubt that this was a BH. Remmed till can confirm one way or the other.) -->\n\nFrom the beginning of the 18th century, this method was gradually superseded by [[reverberatory furnace]] smelting, which used higher temperatures and powdered anthracite as fuel and had the advantage of not requiring a forced draught of air. The smelting house at [[Eylesbarrow tin mine]] which was in operation during the first half of the 19th century had two furnaces, one of each type.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| author = R.M.L. Cook, T.A.P. Grieves & C.C. Kilvington\n| title = Eylesbarrow (1814\u20131852). A Study of a Dartmoor Tin Mine\n| journal = Rep. Trans. Devon. Ass. Advmt Sci.\n| volume = 106\n| pages = 193\u2013198.\n| year = 1974\n| postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nOn Dartmoor, blowing houses were rectangular buildings between around {{convert|16|to|32|ft}} in length and around half this in width.<ref name =\"worth\"/> They were made of unmortared granite blocks with walls often {{convert|2|ft|6|in}} or more thick and probably had turf or thatch roofs which were periodically burnt to retrieve the particles of tin that would have been driven into the roof through the blast from the bellows.<ref name=gill/> Blowing houses are typically located on or near the bank of a stream where the fall of water was enough for a leat to be built to work a small ({{convert|9|ft|abbr=on|disp=or}}) diameter overshot [[water wheel]] which developed around {{Convert|0.66|hp|kW|1|abbr=on}} to operate the bellows.<ref name=gill>{{cite book\n| last =Gill\n| first =Crispin (editor)\n| title =Dartmoor, A New Study\n| publisher =David & Charles\n| year =1970\n| location =Newton Abbot\n| pages =[https://archive.org/details/dartmoornewstudy0000gill/page/102 102\u2013104]\n| isbn =0-7153-5041-2\n| url-access =registration\n| url =https://archive.org/details/dartmoornewstudy0000gill/page/102\n}}</ref>\n\nThe only contemporary detailed description of a blowing house was provided by a Cornishman named [[William Pryce]] in his treatise on Cornish mining of 1778:<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n{{cquote|The fire-place, or castle, is about six feet perpendicular, two feet wide in the top part each way, and about fourteen inches in the bottom, all made of moorstone and clay, well cemented and clamped together. The pipe or nose of each bellows is fixed ten inches (254 mm) high from the bottom of the castle, in a large piece of wrought iron, called the Hearth-eye. The tin and charcoal are laid in the castle, stratum super stratum, in such quantities as are thought proper; so that from eight to twelve hundred weight of Tin, by the consumption of eighteen to twenty-four sixty gallon packs of charcoal, may be smelted in a tide or twelve hours time.<ref>{{Cite book\n| author = [[William Pryce]]\n| title = Mineralogia Cornubiensis: A Treatise on Minerals, Mines, and Mining\n| location = London\n| year = 1778\n| url = https://archive.org/details/mineralogiacorn00prycgoog\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/mineralogiacorn00prycgoog/page/n183 136]\n| publisher = Printed and sold for the author by J. Phillips\n}} (online at Google Books)</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Crispin Gill, about two tons of [[charcoal]] was needed to smelt a ton of metal. The molten metal ran out from the bottom of the furnace into a granite trough or \"float\" from where it was ladled into stone moulds.<ref name=gill/>\n\n==Archaeology==\nArchaeological investigation of blowing houses started in 1866 when John Kelly examined the lower mill at Yealm Steps. Robert Burnard cleared the interior of the lower mill at Week Ford in the 1880s, but the most notable researcher of the remains on Dartmoor was [[Richard Hansford Worth|R. Hansford Worth]] who made detailed records of over 40 sites.<ref name=\"newman\">{{Cite book\n| last = Newman\n| first = Phil\n| title = The Dartmoor Tin Industry \u2013 A Field Guide\n| publisher = Chercombe Press\n| location = Newton Abbot\n| year = 1998\n| pages = 5, 7, 35\u201340\n| isbn = 0-9532708-0-7\n}}</ref> Since then, research on the tin industry in the south west has continued, for instance The Dartmoor Tinworking Interest Group was formed in 1991.<ref name=\"newman\"/>\n\n[[File:Lower blowing house, River Walkham - furnace, float & mould.jpg|thumb|The furnace area of the Lower Merrivale blowing house (see text)]]\nThere is evidence for furnaces that match the description given by Pryce (see above) at Upper and Lower [[Merrivale, Devon|Merrivale]], Avon Dam and Blacksmith's Shop. Each of these sites has two upright granite slabs about {{convert|2|to|3|ft}} apart set into the floor area of the mill, leaving space behind for the bellows. The Merrivale sites also have a slab at the back, making a basic hearth shape.<ref name=\"newman\"/> The accompanying photograph shows the two side slabs of the furnace at the Lower Merrivale blowing house, with the somewhat displaced float stone between them. The mouldstone, filled with rainwater, is just above and to the right.\n\nThe mouldstone is the best field evidence for a blowing house; they are large blocks of granite with a flat top containing a rectangular hollow recess into which the molten tin was poured to be cast into ingots. The moulds vary in size and shape, the largest known from Dartmoor being that from Upper Merrivale at {{convert|280|x|390|mm}}, and the smallest {{convert|180|mm}} square at Longstone. Some mouldstones have additional smaller hollows on their surface; these are traditionally assumed to be for assaying purposes, but some authors have suggested that they may